action.notes:
Initial attempt at generating a meaningful visualization

The raycast-mapper seems to have problems with the datasets involved.
Attempted to modify the visualization by including a colomap to color the various scalar values in the dataset.

The values in the datset seem to be offset by a scalar. I believe this is the result of the scanner producing some outlying values, so I am trying to overcome this with an appropriate color and opacity map.

To initially explore the dataset, I am using a simple linear opacity function. This is appropriate as I anticipate boney material to belong to the high-end of the scalar field. However, this simple exploration will supress some of the low-density material requiring futher exploration once the upper-bound of the scalar field (bone) is determined.

I have realized that the voxel size is incorrect in the z-axis. The reparameterization of the vtkVolume module reflects the correction here. The proper parameterization was initially found via a bulk change to the z-axis parameter stepping from 1.0 to 3.5 in steps of 0.25 it was later verified that the proper spacing should be 2.75

I have realized that the quality of the visualizations has been poor because of a fault in vtk. Its volumeRaycastMapper cannot handle non-byte scalar fields. Re-quantizing the data to [0,255] is undesirable as much of the data from the scanner will be lost regardless of the sampling and quantization techniques we would use. Instead, I have change the visualization pipeline to use a texture-based mapper. This allieviates the restriction of the raycastMapper, but introduces some new sampling issues which must be more thoroughly explored.
As in the xferFunc-1 node, this visualization is using the texture-based mapper. I have found a method for including illumination to the visualization making it more complete and informative.

Just like the parent node, but this visualization includes cutting planes through the data allowing the interior regions of the lungs to be seen. The cutting planes were chosen in order to highlight the location, size, and movement of the lesion in the patient's right lung.

All parameters have been indentified and explored that modify the underlying data. This node contains the visualization of the data with a decent transfer function in both the color and opacity domains. However, additional cutting planes and a more detailed transfer function would help this pipeline.

Like its sibling, this visualization contains a transfer function highlighting the lesion and its movement in time. This visualization lacks much of the interior structure of the lung and makes the visualization as a whole more productive in terms of locating and analyzing the movement of the lesion only.

A very good transfer function has been found to highlight not only the lesion in the right lung, but also the surrounding soft tissues. 2 cutting planes are in place to remove the extraneous parts of the dataset (the scanner couch) and to allow access to the interior of the chest cavity.

A default camera position and orientation has been assigned to make things easier. The default is the Saggital view.

Note: This is capable of easy propogation to any other pipeline by way of analogy.

Set the vtkRenderer to disallow the camera reset that happens upon interaction. This preserves the orientation and position of the camera and ensures that any zoom and translate operations performed will not change the basic orientation of the camera.
